                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18480515-1435-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18480515-1435-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="royalOffences"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18480515-1435-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="coiningOffences"></interp>, unlawfully uttering counterfeit coin.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DAWSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480515-name-1389" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1389" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1389" type="surname" value="COX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1389" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA COX.</persName>
                  </hi> On 22nd April, about seven in the evening, Thompson came to my mistress's shop for a halfpenny-worth of thread—I served her—she gave me a fourpenny-piece—I put it into the till, and gave her 3 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. change—she went away—there were half-crowns and shillings in the till, but no small money—I am sure there was no fourpenny-piece—after she was gone Troson came in—I went to the till and gave him the fourpenny-piece I re-ceived from Thompson—I identify it by a mark on it—no one bad been is the shop from the time Thompson came till Troson came</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480515-name-1390" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1390" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1390" type="surname" value="LOCK"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1390" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN LOCK</persName>
                  </hi>. On 22nd April, between six and seven in the evening, Thompson came to my shop for a pennyworth of tea—my wife served her—a man in private clothes at the door beckoned to me—Thompson gave my wife a fourpenny-piece—she laid it on the counter—I went round and took it up—it was bad—I said so—I bit it—Thompson said she did not know it, or something to that effect—soon afterwards the officer brought Robinson in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MRS. LOCK.</hi> I served Thompson—what my husband has stated is true.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480515-name-1391" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1391" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1391" type="surname" value="TROSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1391" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS TROSON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 337.) On 22nd April, between six and seven in the evening, I was on duty in plain clothes, in Union-street, South-wark—I saw the prisoners in company and followed them—Thompson went into Cox's shop—Robinson stood in the street, in sight of the shop—Thompson came out and gave something to Robinson, and they went on</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184805150163"></xptr>
               <p>together—I went in and received this fourpenny-piece—I them followed them to Mr. Lock's—I took Robinson—he threw this fourpenny-piece from his left hand, and said he had not been <hi rend="italic">pitching</hi>—I took him into Mr. Lock's shop, and found on him 5<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 2 1/2<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. in coppers, 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in silver, and twenty-five packets of mustard, tea, pepper, and other things.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480515-name-1392" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1392" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1392" type="surname" value="WEST"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1392" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS WEST</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 249.) I was with Troson on 22nd April, and saw the prisoners in Union-street—Robinson passed something to Thomp-son, about four yards from Cox's shop—Thompson entered the shop—Ro<lb></lb>binson passed the door—Thompson came out, joined Robinson, and gave him something, which he put into his coat-tail pocket—they then walked on to the New-cut—Thompson went into Mr. Lock's—Robinson waited outside, about fifteen yards off—I got this fourpenny-piece from Mr. Lock's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480515-name-1393" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1393" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1393" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480515-name-1393" type="given" value="CALEB EDWARD"></interp>CALEB EDWARD POWELL.</persName>
                  </hi> I am inspector of coin to the Mint—these three fourpenny-pieces are counterfeit—two of them are cast in the same mould.</p>
